  "texts": [
    "The primary component, silica, possesses strong pozzolanic properties, enabling it to react with calcium hydroxide in the presence of water to form compounds that strengthen concrete [19].",
    "In concrete mixes, the ultrafine particles of SF fill the voids left by larger cement particles, thereby increasing the overall density and structural integrity of the concrete [33].",
    "However, due to its fine nature, SF raises the water demand in concrete mixes, requiring the addition of specific admixtures to maintain workability while achieving the desired water/cement ratio.",
    "Beyond improving density, SF also considerably enhances concrete strength and resistance to water and other substances, contributing to greater durability.",
    "It is important to note that in North America, SF is generally more expensive than other SCMs, reflecting its premium qualities and the costs associated with its production and processing [3]."
  ],
